It really is a valley:

There, right in the middle of the Santa Clara Valley, formed by the Santa C=
ruz Mountains on the west and the Diablo Range on the east, lies the once-s=
leepy city of Mountain View. Mountain View was dominated by the U.S. Navy=
=E2=80=99s Moffett Field in 1955, when William Shockley, one of the invento=
rs of the transistor at Bell Labs, returned to neighboring Palo Alto to car=
e for his ailing mother.

Convinced that silicon was a superior material for transistors =E2=80=94 Be=
ll Labs was focused on germanium =E2=80=94 Shockley, unable to hire many Be=
ll Labs co-workers both because of the distance from New Jersey and also hi=
s abusive management style, set up the Shockley Semiconductor Laboratory in=
 1956 in Mountain View with a collection of young scientists. Only a year l=
ater eight of those scientists, led by Robert Noyce and Gordon Moore, fled =
Shockley =E2=80=94=C2=A0he really was a terrible manager =E2=80=94 and set =
up Fairchild Semiconductor, a new division of Fairchild Camera and Instrume=
nt, in neighboring Sunnyvale.

It was Fairchild Semiconductor that gave the tech industry=E2=80=99s home t=
he other half of its name: yes, we talk about =E2=80=9CThe Valley=E2=80=9D,=
 but at least when it comes to tech, we mean Silicon Valley. From TechCrunc=
h in 2014 ( https://techcrunch.com/2014/07/26/the-first-trillion-dollar-sta=
rtup/ ) :

As Fairchild started to grow, employees began to leave the firm to launch n=
ew spin-off businesses. Many of these firms also grew quickly, inspiring ot=
her employees still working at the company=E2=80=A6The growth of these new =
companies started to reshape the region. In just 12 years, the co-founders =
and former employees of Fairchild generated more than 30 spin-off companies=
 and funded many more. By 1970, chip businesses in the San Francisco area e=
mployed a total of 12,000 people=E2=80=A6

The achievements of these companies eventually attracted attention. In 1971=
, a journalist named Don Hoefler wrote an article about the success of comp=
uter chip companies in the Bay Area. The firms he profiled all produced chi=
ps using silicon and were located in a large valley south of San Francisco.=
 Hoefler put these two facts together to create a new name for the region: =
Silicon Valley.

Hoefler=E2=80=99s article and the name he coined have become quite famous, =
but there=E2=80=99s a critical part of his analysis that is often overlooke=
d: Almost all of the silicon chip companies he profiled can be traced back =
to Fairchild and its co-founders.

Companies formed downstream from Fairchild Semiconductor ( https://techcrun=
ch.com/2014/07/26/the-first-trillion-dollar-startup/ )

Still, for all of the massive success downstream from Fairchild Semiconduct=
or, none mattered more, or came to define Silicon Valley in every respect, =
than Intel. Arthur Rock, who had helped the so-called =E2=80=9CTraitorous E=
ight=E2=80=9D find Fairchild Camera and Instrument, funded Intel, and in th=
e process created the compensation structure that came to define Silicon Va=
lley ( https://law.stanford.edu/stanford-lawyer/articles/legal-matters-arth=
ur-rock-on-the-early-venture-capital-decisions-that-sparked-decades-of-inno=
vation/ ). Gordon Moore wrote the roadmap for Intel =E2=80=94 nor more comm=
only known as Moore=E2=80=99s Law ( http://cva.stanford.edu/classes/cs99s/p=
apers/moore-crammingmorecomponents.pdf ) =E2=80=94 which =E2=80=9Cpredicted=
=E2=80=9D that the number of transistors would double at a set rate, both i=
ncreasing compute speed and driving down prices for that compute; =E2=80=9C=
predict=E2=80=9D is in quotes because Moore=E2=80=99s Law was not a physica=
l law, but an economic one, downstream of Intel=E2=80=99s inexorable push f=
or continued improvement. That, by extension, meant that Intel set the pace=
 of innovation for all of technology, not just by making the processors for=
 the PC =E2=80=94 and, in an underrated wave of disruption in the early par=
t of this century, the cloud =E2=80=94 but also by defining the expectation=
s of every software engineer in the entire world.

